Alright, let's get some updates in as promised:

1. What did we want to complete this week:
 New site
 New codebase for MetaHash
 Documentation (README, Miner, Validator, Subtensor Requirements)
 End-to-end testing
 Exploit scenarios
 Communicate to Validators for initial setup

2. What did we accomplish so far:
 New site (Check - will be disclosed with the release)
 New codebase for MetaHash (Check - will be new repo cloned and updated from original Merit)
 Documentation (README done, Miner/Validator docs to be completed, Subtensor has new requirements for `--prune=2000` for validators if they do not have archive node already)
 End-to-end testing , this is on going and we are finalizing this. We need to make sure we have contingency plans in place for use-cases where subtensor nodes are unavaialble or do not have block history - fall back to finney's archive nodes. Performance wise ~ 93s to lookup. This is tolerable as this will be done once an epoch.
 Exploit sceanrios - now this one is stricky and we are trying to cover as many use-cases as we can, this goes for hotkeys that are registering coldkey lists for tracking and potential avenues of abuse. We'll do our best to have testing coverage for most of the scenarios we come up with and bounties will be available for responsible disclosures (you should know what it is, if you don't ping me and we'll work it out)
 Communicate to Validators for initial setup - I already gave heads up to validators that update is coming and will be providing another update in a few days.

Bottom line we are in a very good shape and considering the interesting here and your eager interest in getting this to prod I am sure you'll be responsible and help us fix any production bugs we might run into once this is released, later this week.

Let me explain what is the design we have implemented for this first iteration: 

- **No restrictions**on who can send alpha, as long as they are registered as miners in SN73. We will no longer require them to be miners of other subnets. @Striker will be pleased.
- Validators set weights each epoch so each epoch can be seen as an **'auction'** of sn73 tokens where miners send alpha of others subnets to participate.
- Alpha is valued using **subnet price and adjusted for slippage**. To avoid flash pumps and dumps we calculate average price and slippage over the entire epoch.

A key question arises: Do we value alpha sent in the first block of the autction the same as alpha sent in the final blocks?

We basically have 2 possibilities to go for:

**Uniform-price model**. In this straightforward approach every unit of αlpha submitted during an epoch is rewarded at the same rate. It keeps it simple. The downside is game-theory: miners can coordinate and wait until the epoch’s final block, creating last-minute CHAOS; 
With this approach miners DO NOT compete against each other. Rather, they compete together against the subnet. Subnet can win or loose. And there is no certainty for miners of early blocks on what are they exactly accepting. 

**Bonding-curve model**. Here the discount accepted by miners is fixed and starts low and increases smoothly as more αlpha is sent. Early participants capture a premium and everyone gains certainty. If not enough alpha is sent so that the value of the alpha sent by miners is less than the value of sn73 alpha given that epoch, we burn the excess. 
Downsides are that bond curve is fix and arbitrary (why 10% or 15%) and that "profits" are capped by the bond curve selection. 

Check *proposals.md* in the repo to see how more complex dyncamics could solve some of this problems.

My opinion:
The uniform model is simpler and could yield higher returns for the subnet if miners make suboptimal decisions. However, it also carries the risk of the subnet "losing money" when miners collude. In contrast, the bonding curve shifts competitive pressure onto miners, ensures the subnet always comes out ahead, and offers greater predictability for participants. I prefer the bonding curve design because it simplifies the decision for miners—they either accept the current discount or wait—rather than forcing them to engage in complex timing games with each other, which ironically makes the uniform model less simple in practice.

Would be great to have a discussion during next couple of days about which design you think is better 👀 

In conclusion, it’s clear that the chosen strategy directly impacts how much 'profit' the subnet generates—where profit is defined as the value entering the treasury minus mining emissions. Regardless of the model, as long as a discount exists, we’re supporting DTAO by providing liquidity specially to subnet owners and miners while receiving a stream of discounted alpha. Additionally, any future price appreciation of alpha could amplify returns—though this remains a speculative upside tied to DTAO’s success, and should be approached with caution.

hey guys apologies for the likely stupid question, where SN73 is intended to be an OTC marketplace for large alpha token holders, the miners ( for example) exchange their miners alpha from other SN’s, at a discounted rate, in exchange for SN73 ‘tokens’ ( referred to in that  X thread) which i’m assuming, correct me if i’m wrong, is the SN73 alpha. from a holders perspective will this not just apply tremendous sell pressure on the SN73 chart as miners sell their SN73 tokens for liquidity for their OPPEX and crash the price of this SN?

please correct me if i have the wrong idea here

The value prop is that if you hold SN73, you get exposure to the alphas from other subnets. Miners send alpha (at discount) and receive SN73, so they might sell 73. But people holding SN73 then have exposure to those discounted alpha from other SN. 

From there I imagine there can be a lot of different strategies with the treasury, providing liquidity on other subnets via uni v3 pools (and providing liquidity is not free, this usually generate yield), maybe distributing to holders, maybe otc deals with validators that need to stake high amount of alpha from other subnets and then use it to buyback SN73 and burn, etc. I'm not saying these things will happen but these are some possible strategies. 

Also keep in mind that the amount miners can send will always have to match more or less the emissions of the subnet, if they send too much they're losing, if they send less then it can be very profitable for them but then it will attract more miners and balances things out. 

But you're right, as on every SN, there will for sure be a constant sell-pressure from miners, subnets are working like that by design since miners are the ones providing the commodity of the subnet and they need to cover their cost. The challenge of MetaHash is/will be to have a value proposition that is higher than what the miners are providing (giving they are providing at discount so the subnet already has "an edge" on this).  On top of that, add the possible arbitrage between subnets, and the inevitable speculation.
(that's my pov, take this with a grain of salt ^^)
